5 “SECTION 1. (1) The Oregon Statewide Preparedness Authority for Response Training
6 and Intergovernmental Continuity of Imperative Services is established as an office within
7 the Oregon Department of Administrative Services. The office is to be known as and may
8 be cited as SPARTICIS.
9 “(2) The office is under the supervision and control of the State Resilience Officer, who
10 is responsible for the performance of the duties, functions and powers of the office.
11 “(3) For purposes of administration, the State Resilience Officer may organize and reor-
12 ganize the office and appoint administrative personnel as the State Resilience Officer con-
13 siders necessary to properly conduct the work of the office.
14 “(4) The State Resilience Officer may divide the functions of the office into administra-
15 tive divisions. The State Resilience Officer may appoint an individual to administer each di-
16 vision. The administrator of each division serves at the pleasure of the State Resilience
17 Officer and is not subject to the provisions of ORS chapter 240. Each individual appointed
18 under this subsection must be well qualified by technical training and experience in the
19 functions to be performed by the individual.
20 “(5) The office shall:
21 “(a) Provide administrative and operational support for the development of strategic im-
22 provements in facilities and programming;
23 “(b) Provide oversight for prioritization of funding associated with emergency-related
24 equipment and functions implemented throughout this state;
25 “(c) Provide standardization across state agencies for continuity of governance planning,
26 exercises and preparedness;
27 “(d) Serve as a platform for development, implementation and assessment of policies
28 adopted by the State Resilience Officer and provide administrative and operational support
29 as directed by the State Resilience Officer;
30 “(e) Carry out the duties imposed by sections 2 to 11 of this 2026 Act; and
31 “(f) Perform such other duties as may be assigned to the office.
32 “(6) The office shall periodically report to the Legislative Assembly on the office’s activ-
33 ities, priorities and project outcomes.
34 “(7) The office may adopt rules as necessary to carry out its duties.
35 “SECTION 2. (1) SPARTICIS shall oversee state strategy relating to regional facilities
LC 235/HB 4121-2

1 and capacity related to emergency preparedness.
2 “(2) The office shall identify, prioritize and assist in obtaining funding for projects to
3 construct or improve regional facilities.
4 “(3) The office shall ensure that the state has a combination of fixed, mobile and trans-
5 portable supplies that is appropriate for emergency management purposes.
6 “(4) The office shall make expenditures, including grants to local governments, as defined
7 in ORS 174.116, and private entities, that are consistent with the goal of enhancing regional
8 facilities related to emergency management. The office may condition grants on matching
9 contributions or other contributions from recipients.
10 “(5) The office shall monitor the progress of all projects overseen by the office under this
11 section and publish quarterly reports on such progress.
12 “(6) The office shall provide administrative support as necessary to other interagency or
13 intergovernmental bodies related to emergency management.
