1 “(4) Recommendations for structural and systematic improvements.
2 “SECTION 23. ORS 401.913 is amended to read:
3 “401.913. (1) The office of State Resilience Officer is created in the office of the Governor. The
4 office of State Resilience Officer shall direct, implement and coordinate hazard safety and resilience
5 goal setting and state agency planning and preparation to improve hazard safety and resilience, in-
6 cluding but not limited to planning and preparation for safety and resilience during and after
7 earthquake, tsunami, wildfire, flooding and other natural or manmade events.
8 “(2) The State Resilience Officer shall lead statewide efforts to implement the Oregon Resilience
9 Plan, the Natural Hazard Mitigation Plan and other resilience plans adopted by the state.
10 “(3) The State Resilience Officer shall facilitate policy standardization among state
11 agencies, prioritize investments for improving resilience posture and provide regular reports
12 on state agency resilience policy compliance, organizational preparedness, continuity of
13 governance procedures and measures of emergency readiness. Such reports may be made to
14 the Governor, appropriate committees of the Legislative Assembly or relevant public safety
15 advisory boards and commissions.
16 “[(3)] (4) The State Resilience Officer shall lead executive branch agencies in continuity of op-
17 erations planning and continuity of government planning.
18 “[(4)] (5) The Governor shall appoint an individual to serve as the State Resilience Officer,
19 subject to confirmation by the Senate pursuant to Article III, section 4, of the Oregon Constitution.
20 “[(5)] (6) The legislative branch of government and the judicial branch of government shall each
21 select an individual to monitor the effectiveness of hazard safety and resilience planning in their
22 branch.
