24 “RESILIENCE HUBS AND NETWORKS
25
26 “SECTION 29. ORS 409.760 is amended to read:
27 “409.760. (1) As used in this section:
28 “(a) ‘Resilience Hub’ means a physical facility that is created, operated, managed or supported
29 by one or more local residents, local governments, tribal governments, public schools, community-
30 based organizations, faith-based organizations, nonprofit organizations, [or] nongovernmental organ-
31 izations or any other groups or entities located in Oregon, and that:
32 “(A) Supports the needs of community members or tribal communities, facilitates gathering and
33 communication, distributes resources and otherwise enhances quality of life within a community;
34 “(B) Serves as a central point for gathering, information sharing, and coordination in response
35 to a disruption in the community;
36 “(C) Enhances the ability of a community to respond to and recover from a disruption in a
37 community;
38 “(D) Is positioned, operated and resourced on a day-to-day basis, during a disruption and
39 during recovery, to provide community resources, including but not limited to food, water, infor-
40 mation exchange, electronic charging stations, basic medical supplies and equipment proportionate
41 to the size of the community’s population and needs;
42 “(E) Supports community cache sites and other support for community members who shelter in
43 place;
44 “(F) Can provide child care, training, food distribution and other services that can help a com-
45 munity respond to unmet [social] needs to prepare for, respond to and recover from adverse events,
HA to HB 4121 Page 11

1 emergencies or disasters;
2 “(G) Can provide, or can be retrofitted to provide, heating, cooling, air filtration and weather
3 protection; and
4 “(H) Accommodates individuals with accessibility needs.
5 “(b) ‘Resilience Network’ means an association of facilities, organizations, resource providers
6 or service providers [outside of a physical Resilience Hub facility that collectively serve the purposes
7 of a Resilience Hub] that collectively supports community members to prepare for, adapt to
8 or respond to social, emotional and physical disruption generated by ongoing climate change
9 or other causes, and during and after an adverse event, emergency or disaster.
10 “(2) The Department of Human Services shall, in consultation with the State Department of
11 Energy and the Oregon Health Authority, provide grants, [support and technical assistance for]
12 equipment, technical assistance, contracted services and any other type of support to indi-
13 viduals or organizations located in Oregon for creating or sustaining Resilience Hubs and
14 Resilience Networks in Oregon. The Department of Human Services shall award:
15 “(a) Grants for expenses related to planning and organizing Resilience Hubs and Resilience
16 Networks;
17 “(b) Grants to support and expand development and operation of Resilience Hubs and Resilience
18 Networks to ensure that physical facilities can provide protection from extreme weather, can
19 maintain power and climate during power outages, have auxiliary communications capabilities and
20 are resilient following earthquakes, fires, tornadoes, floods, other extreme weather events and other
21 potential adverse events, emergencies or disasters[, emergencies or incidents]; and
22 “(c) Grants for resources and services needed by communities to otherwise prepare for and re-
23 spond to adverse events, emergencies or disasters.
24 “(3) Individuals or organizations located in Oregon and serving people in this state may ap-
25 ply for grants by submitting an application that must include:
26 “(a) A description of the purposes for which grant moneys will be expended, including a de-
27 scription of the services to be provided to the community by the Resilience Hub or Resilience
28 Network;
29 “(b) A plan for implementing specific strategies to build resilience in a community;
30 “(c) A description of additional resources available for purposes of the Resilience Hub or
31 Resilience Network;
32 “(d) A description of the project’s ability to serve vulnerable populations and communities tra-
33 ditionally underrepresented in the public process, including communities of color, communities ex-
34 periencing lower incomes, tribal communities, rural communities, coastal communities, communities
35 with limited infrastructure, seniors, youth and persons with disabilities; and
36 “(e) Any other information required by the department.
37 “(4) The department shall execute grant agreements with grant recipients obligating recipients
38 to use grant moneys for purposes specified in the grant agreements. The department, in consultation
39 with the State Department of Energy and the Oregon Health Authority, shall determine the per-
40 missible purposes, applicant eligibility requirements, types of awards for a grant and eligible
41 equipment, technical assistance, services and support under this section based on the needs of
42 the Resilience Hub or Resilience Network. The department shall determine the needs of the
43 Resilience Hub or Resilience Network in consultation with the community, including populations
44 described in subsection (3)(d) of this section, within the locality in which the Resilience Hub or
45 Resilience Network operates.
HA to HB 4121 Page 12

1 “(5) The Department of Human Services shall adopt rules necessary for the administration of
2 this section, including specifying the form and contents of an application for a grant under this
3 section.
4
5 “OVERNIGHT TRAINING ACTIVITIES
6
7 “SECTION 30. Notwithstanding any other provision of state or local law, a facility that
8 receives funding under section 15 of this 2026 Act is authorized to host overnight training
9 activities.
10
11 “COUNTY AUTHORITY TO WAIVE CIVIL PENALTIES
12
13 “SECTION 31. A county governing body may, by order or resolution, waive a civil penalty
14 imposed by the Oregon Health Authority or a local health authority under ORS 624.992 if the
15 civil penalty is imposed for a violation that occurred during a state of emergency declared
16 under ORS 401.165.
17
18 “ONGOING PROGRAM FUNDING
19
20 “SECTION 32. On or before July 1, 2027, the standing or interim Joint Committee on
21 Ways and Means shall identify a sustainable, ongoing revenue source to pay for programs
22 at facilities funded under section 15 of this 2026 Act.
23
24 “DEPARTMENT OF THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL
25
26 “SECTION 33. The Department of the State Fire Marshal shall conduct a study of health
27 coverage disparities between paid and volunteer firefighters. The department shall submit a
28 report in the manner provided by ORS 192.245, and may include recommendations for legis-
29 lation, to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to emergency man-
30 agement no later than September 15, 2027.
31 “SECTION 34. Section 33 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2028.
32
33 “FINGERPRINTING BY ODEM
34
35 “SECTION 35. For the purpose of requesting a state or nationwide criminal records check
36 under ORS 181A.195, the Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall require the
37 fingerprints of a person who:
38 “(1) Is employed or applying for employment by the department; or
39 “(2) Provides or seeks to provide services to the department as a contractor, subcon-
40 tractor, vendor or volunteer.
41
42 “PUBLIC AND INDIVIDUAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAMS
43
44 “SECTION 36. Sections 37 to 40 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS
45 chapter 401.
HA to HB 4121 Page 13

1 “SECTION 37. (1) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall establish and
2 administer a state infrastructure emergency recovery grant program, to be known as the
3 Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program, to issue grants to qualified recipients, subject to
4 available funding.
5 “(2) Grants under the program must be used to pay for work performed before, during
6 or after an emergency to protect public health, safety or property, including, without limi-
7 tation, debris removal and work to protect or restore public services or public
8 infrastructure.
9 “(3) The Governor may activate the program if:
10 “(a) The Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and finds
11 that assistance from the state is warranted; and
12 “(b) The department recommends that the program be activated.
13 “(4) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
14 from the state is no longer warranted.
15 “(5) While the program is active, the department may issue grants to qualified recipients
16 pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may be
17 made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
18 writing and must include the following information:
19 “(a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
20 gency plan;
21 “(b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
22 the impact of the emergency on the public and private sectors;
23 “(c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
24 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency;
25 “(d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
26 assistance needed; and
27 “(e) A certification by the requester that the obligations and expenditures for the current
28 emergency will comply with all applicable cost sharing requirements agreed between the de-
29 partment and the requester.
30 “(6) The department may adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of this
31 section, including rules governing eligibility requirements, the form and manner of requests
32 and evaluation of requests by the department.
33 “(7) As used in this section, ‘qualified recipient’ means:
34 “(a) A state agency;
35 “(b) A local government;
36 “(c) A federally recognized Indian tribe in Oregon;
37 “(d) A school district or education service district; and
38 “(e) A nonprofit organization that provides critical services or essential social services,
39 such as a hospital, long term care facility, school, community center, food assistance pro-
40 gram or shelter.
41 “SECTION 38. The Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program Account is established in
42 the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the
43 account must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, al-
44 located, deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise
45 and interest earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously
HA to HB 4121 Page 14

1 appropriated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management to carry out the Oregon
2 Public Assistance Grant Program described in section 37 of this 2026 Act. The department
3 shall ensure that no more than 10 percent of the moneys in the account are used to pay costs
4 of coordination and distribution of assistance under the program.
5 “SECTION 39. (1) The Department of Human Services shall establish and administer an
6 individual grant program, to be known as the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program,
7 to issue grants to address critical emergency-related needs of qualified individuals, subject
8 to available funding.
9 “(2) The Governor may activate the program if:
10 “(a) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management recommends that the program
11 be activated, the Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and
12 the Governor finds that assistance from the state is warranted; or
13 “(b) The Governor has declared an emergency under ORS 401.165.
14 “(3) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
15 from the state is no longer warranted.
16 “(4) While the program is active, the Department of Human Services may issue grants
17 pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may be
18 made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
19 writing and must include the following information:
20 “(a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
21 gency plan;
22 “(b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
23 the impact of the emergency on individuals and households;
24 “(c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
25 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency; and
26 “(d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
27 assistance needed.
28 “(5) Grants under the program may be used only to pay for:
29 “(a) The provision of services to qualified individuals for critical emergency-related
30 needs, which may include, without limitation:
31 “(A) Temporary rental assistance;
32 “(B) Hazard mitigation assistance;
33 “(C) Repair or replacement of owner-occupied homes that serve as a primary residence,
34 including repair or replacement of privately owned access routes;
35 “(D) Assistance with immediate needs;
36 “(E) Essential personal property assistance;
37 “(F) Assistance with other serious needs that are not covered by insurance; and
38 “(G) Other critical emergency recovery services as approved by the Oregon Department
39 of Emergency Management; and
40 “(b) Agreements with local governments, tribal entities or disaster recovery organiza-
41 tions for the delivery of services described in paragraph (a) of this subsection, including
42 payments for staffing or other administrative needs.
43 “(6) Assistance to individuals may be in the form of direct financial assistance or pay-
44 ments to another entity on behalf of individuals.
45 “(7) The Department of Human Services, in consultation with the Oregon Department
HA to HB 4121 Page 15

1 of Emergency Management, may adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of
2 this section.
3 “(8) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management, in consultation with the De-
4 partment of Human Services, shall update the statewide emergency management plan pre-
5 pared under ORS 401.052 to incorporate the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program
6 into statewide disaster response and recovery planning. The plan must include, without lim-
7 itation, provisions for equitable distribution of assistance, coordination with local govern-
8 ments and community-based organizations, and integration with federal recovery programs
9 when applicable.
10 “(9) As used in this section:
11 “(a) ‘Hazard mitigation’ means actions taken to reduce impacts of future emergencies.
12 “(b) ‘Immediate need’ means:
13 “(A) A life-saving or life-sustaining item or activity that is essential to prevent, mitigate
14 or overcome an adverse condition caused by an emergency; and
15 “(B) Other equipment that is essential for daily household needs.
16 “(c) ‘Qualified individual’ means:
17 “(A) An individual who is displaced by an emergency from the individual’s primary resi-
18 dence;
19 “(B) An individual whose primary residence is rendered uninhabitable by an emergency;
20 or
21 “(C) An individual with a disability whose primary residence is rendered inaccessible or
22 uninhabitable to the individual as a result of damage caused by an emergency.
23 “SECTION 40. The Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program Account is established
24 in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the
25 account must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, al-
26 located, deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise
27 and interest earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously
28 appropriated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management. The department may
29 make moneys in the account available to the Department of Human Services to carry out
30 the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program described in section 39 of this 2026 Act.
31
32 “CAPTIONS
33
34 “SECTION 41. The unit captions used in this 2026 Act are provided only for the conven-
35 ience of the reader and do not become part of the statutory law of this state or express any
36 legislative intent in the enactment of this 2026 Act.”.
